\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:SDE-motivation"

\end_inset

Stochastic Differential Equations: Motivation and definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use stochastic differential equations (SDEs) to estimate the power spectral
 density of a time series.
 We motivate this choice over available alternatives as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By using 
\emph on
a parametric model 
\emph default
we can formulate of a maximum likelihood (ML) estimator.
 Unlike many non-parametric estimators, ML estimators have desirable theoretical
 properties such as asymptotic efficiency.
 Parametric spectral estimators have been most successful at achieving the
 benefit of high-frequency spectra in finite samples 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "broersen2007beyondrate"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, whereas non-parametric methods such as the Lomb-Scargle estimator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "springford2020lombscargle"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have very high variance, which mostly limits their use to finding a single
 peak in the spectrum under high signal-to-noise conditions.
 Similarly, in the time domain, correlation estimated with the non-parametric
 slotting technique violate the positive-definiteness property that is required
 for a valid autocorrelation function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rehfeld2011comparison"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Parametric models can achieve the same flexibility as non-parametric estimates
 by increasing the model order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The SDE model is a 
\emph on
continuous time
\emph default
 model, which can operate directly on non-uniform samples without the need
 to introduce a regular grid as is required for discrete-time estimates.
 Moreover, estimated discrete time time series models may have poles that
 do not have a continuous-time counterpart 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "soderstrom1991contarma"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stochastic differential equation of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for the process 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as a function of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{p}y}{dt^{p}}+\sum_{i=1}^{p}a_{i}\frac{d^{i-1}y}{dt}=\epsilon\label{eq:sde}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the SDE coefficients, collectively denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is continuous Gaussian white noise with standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SDE model can be rewritten as an equivalent state-space model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{\ensuremath{\frac{d\mathbb{\mathbf{z}}}{dt}}} & =\mathbf{A}\mathbf{z}+\mathbf{\epsilon}\label{eq:state-space}\\
y & =C\text{\ensuremath{\mathbf{z}}}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-dimensional time series and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\mathbf{z}=z_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 can be computed from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\sigma_{\epsilon}\right\} $
\end_inset

, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jones1981fitcar"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SDE process has a power spectral density given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sarkka2019sde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{y}\left(f\right)=\mathbf{C}\left(\mathbf{A}-i2\pi f\mathbf{I}\right)^{-1}\mathbf{Q}\left(\mathbf{A}+i2\pi f\mathbf{I}\right)^{-T}\mathbf{C}^{T}
\]

\end_inset

and the covariance function at lag 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau>0$
\end_inset

 of:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R\left(\tau\right)=\mathbf{\mathbf{P}}_{s}\exp\left(\mathbf{A}t\right)^{T}\label{eq:autocov}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{P}}_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the stationary covariance matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state space equation may be diagonalized to represent the SDE as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{\ensuremath{\frac{d\mathbb{\mathbf{z}}'}{dt}}} & =\Lambda\mathbb{\mathbf{z}}'+\mathbf{\epsilon'}\\
y= & C'\text{\ensuremath{\mathbf{z}}}'
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the eigenvalues are equal to the the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 (collectively denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

) of the characteristic equation of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sde"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C'\text{\ensuremath{\mathbf{z}}}'=\sum z'_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We refer to this parameterization as the 
\series bold
roots parameterization
\series default
, while we refer to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{a},\sigma_{\epsilon}\right\} $
\end_inset

 parameterization as the 
\series bold
coefficients
\series default
 
\series bold
parameterization
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key advantage of the roots parameterization is that stationarity can
 be expressed as the requirement that the real part of the roots is negative
 : 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Re}\left(r_{i}\right)<0$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the computational complexity of the likelihood computation
 is more efficient for large model order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the advantages, many researchers use the coefficient representation.
 This may be motivated by the reduced computational complexity for lower-order
 models.
 In addition, SDEs can be used to parameterize a kernel as part of a larger
 machine learning model, e.g.
 in deep learning models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chen2018neuralode"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or for posterior sampling using a probabilistic program 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "carpenter2017stan"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Currently many major automatic differentiation packages such as PyTorch
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "paszke2017pytorch-autodiff"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the Stan autodiff library 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "carpenter2015stan-autodiff"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 do not support complex-valued parameters, therefore necessitating the use
 of the coefficient representation.
 Therefore, we consider both representations in this work.
\end_layout

