Maximum likelihood estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Likelihood computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exact log likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is computed recursively using the Kalman filtering equations.
 Process stationarity is exploited for the first observation, i.e., it has
 the stationary covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Given a value for the SDE parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

, the analytical expression for the Maximum Likelihood standard deviation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jones1981fitcar"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For unstable models, or errors due to the finite machine precision, a log
 likelihood of 
\begin_inset Formula $L=-\infty$
\end_inset

 is produced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The computation largely follows cited algorithms, with the following improvement
s to increase computational efficiency:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the coefficient representation, we follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sarkka2019sde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

