\begin_layout Subsection
Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimization of the likelihood is performed using the Limited-Memory BFGS
 algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nocedal2006optimization"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, with derivatives obtained through automatic differentiation.
 For the coefficient representation, a necessary condition for stability
 is that all coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are positive; it is also sufficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $p\le2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mattuck2011diffeq-stability"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To improve optimization results, parameter values are constrained to a
 configurable interval: 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\langle a_{l},a_{h}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Wide limits should be set to allow for a wide range of models.
 As an indication, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{l}$
\end_inset

 is related to the duration 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 of the time series 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{l}\lesssim1/D$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{h}$
\end_inset

 is related to the shortest sampling interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{h}\gtrsim1/\Delta t_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 In the presented simulation results, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\langle 10^{-3},10^{3}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 In the roots representation, the real and imaginary part of the roots are
 similarly constrained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Initialization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Initialization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Accurate initialization of the optimization is key to achieving high-quality
 estimates.
 The sensitivity of SDE parameter estimation to initial conditions has been
 acknowledged in the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jones1984sensitive-init"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, in particular for higher-order models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "broersen2006sensitive-init"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first element in the algorithm is 
\series bold
incremental estimation
\series default
: The estimate for the SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) model is initiated from a lower order SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

) model (
\begin_inset Formula $p'<p$
\end_inset

).
 The motivation for incremental estimation is the observation that per parameter
, lower order models often have the largest contribution to the model fit.
 The lower order models are expanded by adding a single random real root
 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $p'=p-1$
\end_inset

) or a conjugate pair of random complex roots (for 
\begin_inset Formula $p'=p-2$
\end_inset

) to the lower order model.
 An alternative for a this root initialization would be to use a large initial
 value, as this corresponds to a model that is most similar to the lower-order
 model.
 However, this extreme initialization does not result in successful convergence
 to a finite value during the numerical optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second element is 
\series bold
initiation from autoregressive 
\series default
(AR) 
\series bold
models 
\series default
estimated from resampled data using the Burg estimator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "percival2020spectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Resampling is performed using nearest neighbor interpolation and linear
 interpolation.
 Intentionally, basic interpolation methods are used here, because more
 advanced interpolation methods tend to produce artificially smooth signals,
 or, in the frequency domain, a power spectrum with a very large dynamic
 range.
 This results in less accurate models, since the estimators attempts to
 fit the artificially introduced low power spectral density at high frequencies,
 at the expense of modeling the actual process dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "broersen2006automatic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 AR roots that do not have a corresponding continuous-time root 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "soderstrom1991contarma"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 are replaced by randomly generated roots.
\end_layout

