\begin_layout Subsection
Kullback-Leibler Discrepancy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective is to accurately characterize the second-order moments of
 a random process, which we quantify using the The Kullback-Leibler Discrepancy
 (KLD).
 The KLD has a number of desirable properties.
 First, it has units that are statistically meaningful.
 For an unbiased estimate of a 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 that achieves the Cramér-Rao lower bound, the expected value of the KLD
 is asymptotically equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $d/2$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{E}\left[D\left(\hat{\mathbf{\theta}}\mathbf{\Vert\mathbf{\theta}}\right)\right]=d/2$
\end_inset

.
 For the SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) model we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p+1$
\end_inset

 parameters (adding 1 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

), yielding:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{E}\left[D\left(\hat{\mathbf{\theta}}\mathbf{\Vert\mathbf{\theta}}\right)\right]=\left(p+1\right)/2.\label{eq:expect-kld}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 A second desirable property is that, for time series models, the KLD is
 asymptotically equivalent to the spectral distortion (Root Mean Square
 Error (RMSE) of the log power spectrum) and the normalized one-step ahead
 prediction error.
 See e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "broersen2006automatic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for further background on these properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The KLD for a zero-mean multivariate Gaussian model for a random vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 with covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the true zero-mean distribution with covariance matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\left(\Sigma\Vert\hat{\Sigma}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{tr}\left(\hat{\Sigma}^{-1}\Sigma-I\right)-\log\text{\left(\left|\Sigma\right|/\hat{\left|\Sigma\right|}\right)}\right)\label{eq:kld}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For SDE models, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of time series observations at times 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The covariance matrix is computed using the covariance function from eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:autocov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The choice of time steps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 determines the time scale at which we evaluate the process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is the original time points of the dataset to which the estimated model
 is fitted.
 The resulting KLD is referred to as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{o}$
\end_inset

.
 A second value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{t}$
\end_inset

 is a regularly spaced grid at interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, referred to as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{T}.$
\end_inset

 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the time scale of interest at which we evaluate the second
 order moments.
 In the frequency domain, the corresponds to evaluating the power spectrum
 for frequencies up to the corresponding Nyquist frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1/2T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The KLD does not suffer from some problems associated with some alternative
 ways to evaluate estimates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Look for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

actual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 order
\series default
: Practical processes typically cannot be described exactly by a finite
 order model.
 Even if such a finite order model would exist, estimating a model of this
 order may not result in the most accurate estimate due to estimation errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
RMSE of estimated SDE coefficients or autocovariance
\series default
:
\series bold
 
\series default
A small change coefficients or autocovariance values can result in a completely
 different process, e.g.
 changing from stable to unstable (coefficients), or positive-definite (valid)
 to not positive-definite (invalid) for autocovariances 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rehfeld2011comparison"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The base implementation of the KLD is computationally expensive.
