name "sec:truncation"

\end_inset

Data-driven model truncation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we describe the phenomenon of parameter divergence in SDE
 parameter estimation, and how it can be exploited to reduce the cost of
 model overfit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model truncation for the SDE(1) model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As parameters are optimized to maximize the likelihood, parameter estimates
 can diverge to infinity, resulting in numerical problems in the likelihood
 computation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jones1981fitcar"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Also, it has been reported that not all AR models have a continuous-time
 counterpart 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "soderstrom1991contarma"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this section, we show how these phenomena are closely related through
 a theoretical analysis of the the SDE(1) model.
 Furthermore, we show how this phenomenon ultimately results in more accurate
 estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SDE(1) model is an important model for many applications.
 It is also known in the literature as the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process and
 is a special case of the Matérn kernel 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rasmussen2003gaussian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For data regularly sampled at interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the maximum likelihood estimate of the SDE(1) parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}$
\end_inset

 can be computed analytically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sarkka2019sde"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{a}=\frac{1}{T}\log\left[\hat{\alpha}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated AR(1) parameter.
 For a white noise process, the estimated AR(1) parameter is distributed
 symmetrically around 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}=0$
\end_inset

 with standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "priestley1981spectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is negative for 50% of signals.
 In this case, the AR(1) process has no continuous-time counterpart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be shown that, under these conditions, the likelihood monotonically
 increases for 
\begin_inset Formula $a\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In this limit, the SDE(1) model is equivalent to the white noise model.
 In practice, the true model order is unknown, and so it is critical that
 an estimator returns an accurate estimate under these circumstances.
 This is achieved using data-driven model truncation.
 With model trunction, the estimation algorithm for an SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) model can return a lower SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

) model if the likelihood indicates that the lower order model fits better
 to the data.
 For the SDE(1) case, this amounts in returning an SDE(0) or white noise
 model when 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}<0$
\end_inset

.
 We discuss model truncation for higher order models in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model truncation for higher order models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Initialization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) models are estimated incrementally.
 If parameter divergence occurs, the model returned by the optimization
 procedure has large but finite values because of the limits introduced
 on parameter values.
 In this case, the lower order model will have a larger likelihood, and
 is consequently the final maximum likelihood estimate.
 While this phenomena can be easily analyzed for the SDE(1) model estimated
 from white noise, this is an important phenomena more generally, as it
 occurs whenever the order of the estimated model is greater than the true
 model order.
 Since the true model order is unknown for experimental data, it is desirable
 to estimate a high order model, so that a wide range of processes can be
 represented.
 Model truncation reduces the cost of overfit, i.e., the statistical estimation
 error induced by estimation SDE(
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) models where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 exceeds the true model order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
