Analysis of monsoon rainfall variability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Long-term variability in monsoon rainfall is studied using radiometric-dated,
 speleothem oxygen isotope 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{18}O$
\end_inset

 records 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sinha2015trends"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The data is intrinsically irregularly sampled, because it is formed by
 natural deposition rather than experimenter controlled sampling.
 For the same reason, irregular sampling occurs for many other long-term
 climate records as well, e.g.
 ice core data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "petit1999climate"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average sampling rate of speleothem data depends on the measurement
 location.
 The current dataset is suitable for algorithm benchmarking because it has
 a higher average sampling rate than datasets collected from other locations.
 This allows us to study algorithm performance for different sampling rates,
 by subsampling the original data, and comparing the results to estimates
 obtained from the full dataset.
 Also, the dataset is publicly available as supplementary material to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sinha2015trends"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for reproducibility of results.
 The oxygen isotope data consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1848$
\end_inset

 irregularly sampled observations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{18}O$
\end_inset

 anomalies over a time span of 
\begin_inset Formula $2147$
\end_inset

 years, resulting in average sampling interval of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}=1.16$
\end_inset

 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate SDE(8) models from detrended 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{18}O$
\end_inset

 data.
 A reference estimate is obtained using the complete dataset.
 To emulate a lower sampling rate, we then estimate models from 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 random subsets of the original data, at an average sampling interval of
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{av}=5$
\end_inset

 years.
 The resulting estimated spectra and model fit are given in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:monsoon-psd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The reference SDE(8) model is truncated to an SDE(1) model.
 Models estimated from the subsampled data similarly exploit model truncation
 to achieve accurate spectral estimates, avoiding erroneous peaks in the
 estimate, despite a much lower sampling frequency compared to the full
 dataset.
 The maximum likelihood is achieved at either order 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 (4 out of 5 subsets) or 
\begin_inset Formula $p=5$
\end_inset

 (1/5) (see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:monsoon-psd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, bottom).
\end_layout

